sentence: What is the highest mountain in Germany?

sentence: Which American presidents were in office during the Vietnam War?
sparqlQald: PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/> PREFIX res: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/> PREFIX dct: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> PREFIX dbc: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/Category:> SELECT ?uri WHERE { ?uri dct:subject dbc:Presidents_of_the_United_States . res:Vietnam_War dbo:commander ?uri }
sparql:
PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dbc: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/Category:>

SELECT ?president
WHERE {
   ?president dbo:officeDuring ?term .
   ?term dbo:war dbo:Vietnam_War .
   ?president dbo:nationality dbc:Presidents_of_the_United_States .
}
ORDER BY ?president

sentence: Butch Otter is the governor of which U.S. state?

sparql:
SELECT ?stateLabel WHERE {
  ?otter foaf:name "Butch Otter"@en.
  ?otter dbp:office ?office.

}

sentence: How many gold medals did Michael Phelps win at the 2008 Olympics?
sparqlQald: PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/> PREFIX dbr: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/> PREFIX rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> PREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> SELECT Count(?sub) as ?c WHERE { ?sub dbo:goldMedalist dbr:Michael_Phelps . filter (contains (str(?sub), "2008") && contains (str(?sub), "Olympics")) }
sparql:
PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dbp: <http://dbpedia.org/property/>
PREFIX res: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/>

SELECT (COUNT(DISTINCT ?medal) AS ?goldMedals)
WHERE {
  ?phelps dbo:goldMedals ?medal .
  ?medal dbp:games res:2008_Summer_Olympics .
  FILTER(CONTAINS(LCASE(str(?phelps)), "michael_phelps"))
}

sentence: How many seats does the home stadium of FC Porto have?

sentence: Which frequent flyer program has the most airlines?
sparqlQald: SELECT ?uri WHERE { ?airline <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Airline> . ?airline <http://dbpedia.org/property/frequentFlyer> ?uri. } GROUP BY ?uri ORDER BY DESC(COUNT(DISTINCT ?airline)) OFFSET 0 LIMIT 1
sparql:
PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dbp: <http://dbpedia.org/property/>
PREFIX dbr: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/>

SELECT ?programName (COUNT(?airline) AS ?airlineCount)
WHERE {
    ?program a dbo:Program ;
             dbp:name ?programName .
    ?airline dbo:owner ?program .
}
GROUP BY ?programName
ORDER BY DESC(?airlineCount)
LIMIT 1

sentence: Which countries have places with more than two caves?
sparqlQald: PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/> PREFIX rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> SELECT DISTINCT ?uri WHERE { ?cave rdf:type dbo:Cave ; dbo:location ?uri . ?uri rdf:type dbo:Country } GROUP BY ?uri HAVING ( COUNT(?cave) > 2 )
sparql:
SELECT DISTINCT ?country WHERE {
  ?place rdf:type dbo:Place.
  ?place dbo:country ?country.
  ?place dbo:caves ?caves.
  FILTER(?caves > 2).
}
GROUP BY ?country
ORDER BY ?country

sentence: What is the highest place of Karakoram?
sparqlQald: PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/> PREFIX res: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/> SELECT DISTINCT ?uri WHERE { res:Karakoram dbp:highest ?uri }
sparql:
The following SPARQL query can be used to retrieve the highest place in Karakoram from DBpedia:

```sparql
PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dbr: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/>

SELECT ?highestPlace
WHERE {
  ?highestPlace dbo:mountainRange dbr:Karakoram ;
               dbo:elevation ?elevation .
}
ORDER BY DESC(?elevation)
LIMIT 1
```

This query selects the ?highestPlace variable and retrieves the place that belongs to the mountain range "Karakoram". It also retrieves the ?elevation of each place. The results are then ordered in descending order based on the ?elevation, and only the top 1 result is returned using the `LIMIT 1` clause.

sentence: Which U.S. state has the highest population density?

sentence: Which poet wrote the most books?
sparqlQald: SELECT DISTINCT ?uri WHERE { ?uri <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/occupation> <http://dbpedia.org/resource/Poet> . ?x <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/author> ?uri . ?x <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/Book> . } ORDER BY DESC(COUNT(?x)) OFFSET 0 LIMIT 1
sparql:
PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dct: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/>

SELECT ?poetName (COUNT(?book) AS ?numBooks)
WHERE {
  ?poet dbo:occupation dbr:Poet .
  ?poet dct:subject ?poetSubject .
  ?book dct:subject ?poetSubject .
  ?poet foaf:name ?poetName .
}
GROUP BY ?poetName
ORDER BY DESC(?numBooks)
LIMIT 1

sentence: Give me all gangsters from the prohibition era.

sparql:
SELECT ?gangster
WHERE {
  ?gangster a dbo:Person .
  ?gangster dct:subject dbc:American_gangsters .

}

sentence: Give me all American presidents of the last 20 years.

sentence: What languages are spoken in Pakistan?
sparqlQald: SELECT DISTINCT ?uri WHERE { <http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pakistan> <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/language> ?uri }
sparql:
PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dbr: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/>

SELECT ?languageLabel
WHERE {
  dbr:Pakistan dbo:language ?language .
  ?language rdfs:label ?languageLabel .
  FILTER(LANG(?languageLabel) = 'en')
}

This SPARQL query retrieves the languages spoken in Pakistan from DBPEDIA by searching the dbo:language property of the resource dbr:Pakistan. It selects the rdfs:label of each language, filtering the results to only include English language labels. This ensures that the retrieved language labels are in English.

sentence: Which daughters of British earls died at the same place they were born at?
sparqlQald: PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/> PREFIX yago: <http://dbpedia.org/class/yago/> PREFIX rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> SELECT DISTINCT ?uri WHERE { ?uri rdf:type yago:WikicatDaughtersOfBritishEarls ; dbo:birthPlace ?x ; dbo:deathPlace ?y FILTER ( ?x = ?y ) }
sparql:
PREFIX rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#>
PREFIX dbpedia-owl: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dbpedia: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/>
PREFIX foaf: <http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/>

SELECT DISTINCT ?daughter ?birthPlace ?deathPlace
WHERE {
    ?daughter dbpedia-owl:birthPlace ?birthPlace;
             dbpedia-owl:deathPlace ?deathPlace.

    ?daughter dbpedia-owl:parent ?parent.
    ?parent rdf:type dbpedia-owl:Earl.
    ?parent dbpedia-owl:nationality dbpedia:United_Kingdom.
    
    FILTER(?birthPlace = ?deathPlace).
}
LIMIT 10

sentence: Who is the novelist of the work a song of ice and fire?
sparqlQald: PREFIX dbr: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/> PREFIX dbp: <http://dbpedia.org/property/> SELECT ?Novelist WHERE { dbr:A_Song_of_Ice_and_Fire dbp:author ?Novelist }
sparql:
The SPARQL query for finding the novelist of the work "A Song of Ice and Fire" in DBpedia is as follows:

```
SELECT ?novelistLabel
WHERE {
  ?novel rdf:type dbo:Work.
  ?novel rdfs:label "A Song of Ice and Fire"@en.
  ?novel dbo:author ?novelist.
  ?novelist rdf:type dbo:Writer.
  ?novelist rdfs:label ?novelistLabel.
  FILTER(LANG(?novelistLabel) = "en").
}
```

This query selects the `?novelistLabel` (which represents the name of the novelist) where the `?novel` has the label "A Song of Ice and Fire" in English (`@en`), and the `?novel` has an `dbo:author` (author) who is of type `dbo:Writer`. It then applies a `FILTER` to only retrieve the `?novelistLabel` in English language.

Please note that the query result may include various variations of the novelist's name due to different labels used in DBpedia.

sentence: Give me the capitals of all countries in Africa.
sparqlQald: PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/> PREFIX dbc: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/Category:> PREFIX dct: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> SELECT DISTINCT ?uri WHERE { ?country dct:subject dbc:Countries_in_Africa ; dbo:capital ?uri }
sparql:
```
PREFIX dbo: <http://dbpedia.org/ontology/>
PREFIX dbr: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/>
PREFIX dct: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/>
PREFIX dbc: <http://dbpedia.org/resource/Category:>

SELECT ?country ?capital WHERE {
  ?country dct:subject dbc:Countries_in_Africa .
  ?country dbo:capital ?capital .
}
```

In this SPARQL query, we first specify prefixes for the dbo (DBpedia ontology), dbr (DBpedia resource), dct (Dublin Core terms), and dbc (DBpedia category). We then select the variables ?country and ?capital.

We use the WHERE clause to specify the conditions of our query. First, we find entities that have the category "Countries in Africa" in the subject field. Then, we find the capital of each selected country using the dbo:capital property.

This query will retrieve the names of all countries in Africa along with their corresponding capitals.
